Sorta — third-party data attribution
=====================================

This project bundles and/or queries geographic data from third parties.
Sorta's own source code is MIT-licensed (see LICENSE); the notices below
cover only the data, not the code.

1. GeoNames (bundled, offline reverse geocoding)
-------------------------------------------------
`data/geo/*.tsv` (countries.tsv, admin1.tsv, places.tsv, names.tsv) are
derived from the GeoNames geographical database (https://www.geonames.org/),
built via `scripts/build_geodata.py` from a GeoNames `cities1000` export.

GeoNames is made available under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0
License (CC BY 4.0): https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/

  Data source: GeoNames (https://www.geonames.org/), CC BY 4.0.

This attribution satisfies the CC BY 4.0 requirement for any product
that redistributes GeoNames-derived data, including Sorta's offline
`geo.provider: offline` mode (the default — no network access involved).

2. OpenStreetMap / Nominatim (optional, online reverse geocoding)
-------------------------------------------------------------------
When a user explicitly enables `geo.provider: online` in `config.yaml`,
Sorta sends GPS coordinates (never images) to a Nominatim reverse-geocoding
endpoint (default: https://nominatim.openstreetmap.org) to resolve places
more accurately for locations outside the bundled GeoNames coverage.

OpenStreetMap data is © OpenStreetMap contributors, available under the
Open Database License (ODbL): https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright

Sorta's Nominatim client identifies itself with a fixed User-Agent
(`geo.nominatim_user_agent`, default `sorta-photo-organizer`) and
throttles requests to at most one per second, per the Nominatim usage
policy: https://operations.osmfoundation.org/policies/nominatim/

This feature is opt-in and off by default; see SECURITY.md for the
full privacy discussion.
